  "prompt": "Does Gary Johnson have any chance left at winning the presidency?",
  "response": "As of the 2024 election cycle, Gary Johnson, the former Libertarian Party presidential candidate in 2012 and 2016, is not currently a major contender for the presidency. In the 2016 election, Johnson received about 3.3% of the popular vote, marking one of the best performances by a Libertarian candidate, but it was far short of what would be needed to win the presidency.\n\nFor the 2024 election, Johnson has not emerged as a significant candidate in either the Libertarian Party or the broader political landscape. The Libertarian Party has not yet selected its nominee, and it remains unclear whether Johnson or another candidate will represent the party. Historically, third-party candidates face significant challenges in U.S. presidential elections due to the dominance of the Democratic and Republican parties, limited media coverage, and structural barriers like ballot access and debate participation.\n\nIn summary, while it's theoretically possible for a third-party candidate to win the presidency, the political environment and historical trends suggest that Gary Johnson or any Libertarian candidate has a very slim chance of winning in 2024. The focus remains primarily on the Democratic and Republican candidates.",
